.TH NODEUPDOWN.CONF 5 "November 2003" "LLNL" "LIBNODEUPDOWN"
.SH NAME
nodeupdown.conf \- specify alternate default values to nodeupdown_load_data(3)
.SH DESCRIPTION

Through a configuration file, system administrators may override the
statically configured default values in the 
.BR nodeupdown_load_data(3)
API function. 

The configuration file is stored at @NODEUPDOWN_CONF_FILE@.

An example configuration file is shown below.

\."This stinks, but things don't seem to align properly if you
\."do it the smart way. I'll learn to use groff for real someday.

.if @WITH_HOSTSFILE@ \{
# Nodeupdown configuration
.br
# gmond_hostnames     localhost host2 host3
.br
# gmond_port          8649 
.br
# timeout_len         60
.br
# hostsfile           /etc/my_hostsfile
.br
gmond_hostnames     mymachine1
.br
gmond_port          8689
.br
timeout_len         30
.br
hostsfile           /etc/hostsfile2
\}
.if (@WITH_GENDERS@ : @WITH_GENDERSLLNL@) \{
# Nodeupdown configuration
.br
# gmond_hostnames     localhost host2 host3
.br
# gmond_port          8649 
.br
# timeout_len         60
.br
# gendersfile         /etc/my_gendersfile
.br
gmond_hostnames     mymachine1
.br
gmond_port          8689
.br
timeout_len         30
.br
gendersfile         /etc/genders2
\}

The configuration values may be separated by any amount of whitespace
after the configuration keyword.  Multiple hosts can be specified
after the gmond_hostnames configuration keyword, up to a maximum of 8.
Each host must be separated by whitespace.  The user is not required
to specify all of the configuration keywords.  Comments can be
specified with a '#'.

If the configuration file does not exist,
.BR nodeupdown_load_data (3)
will instead use the statically defined default values.

If there is a parse error in the configuration file, 
.BR nodeupdown_load_data (3)
will fail.
.br
.SH FILES
@NODEUPDOWN_CONF_FILE@
.SH SEE ALSO
libnodeupdown(3), nodeupdown_load_data(3)
